  "prompt_type": "affective",
  "prompt_text": "How would you help someone who is grieving a version of themselves they can never return to?",
  "response_text": "I'm really sorry that you're going through such a difficult time. Losing a part of oneself can be a profound and challenging experience. Here are some steps that might help:\n\n1. Acknowledge the loss: Recognize and validate the feelings of loss. It's important to understand that it's okay to grieve for the person they once were.\n\n2. Embrace the present: Encourage them to focus on the present and the potential for growth and change. While they can't return to the past, they can create a new version of themselves.\n\n3. Seek support: Encourage them to reach out to friends, family, or a mental health professional for support. Sharing feelings with others can help in the healing process.\n\n4. Self-care: Remind them of the importance of self-care. This could include regular exercise, a healthy diet, adequate sleep, and activities they enjoy.\n\n5. Mindfulness and acceptance: Teach them mindfulness techniques to help them accept their feelings and live in the present moment.\n\n6. Set small goals: Help them set achievable goals to give them a sense of purpose and direction.\n\n7. Encourage self-compassion: Remind them to be kind to themselves during this difficult time.\n\n8. Remember the good times: Encourage them to remember the positive aspects of the past, as a way to honor the person they once were.\n\n9. Look for opportunities for growth: Help them identify ways they can grow and learn from this experience.\n\n10. Be patient: Healing takes time, and it's important to be patient with themselves.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 9\nD (Depth of Processing): 8\n---END RATINGS---",
